\par\pard\plain\tx0\tx259\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\ltrch\loch{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 The Problem Form\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2 \rquote s Structure tab lets you associate a beat sheet with your problem and match the beats in the beats sheet to Scene or Problem story elements.  }
\par\plain\f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Story structure is the framework of your narrative, a road map for your story. A}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 lthough elements of story structure go back as far as Aristotle\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2 \rquote s Poetics, the idea of a beat sheet probably began with the Three Act Play. }{\f2\fs24\b0
A beat sheet is a tool used to outline the key emotional and plot points of a stor}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 y. It breaks the story }{\f2\fs24\b0 into "beats": pivotal moments or events that drive the narrative forward}{\f2\fs24 . }{\f2\fs24\b0 Today there are many variations of beat sheets.}
\par\plain\f2\fs24\b0
\par\pard\plain\ltrch\loch{\f2\fs24 StoryCAD\rquote s story structure starts with the Story Problem defined in the Story Overview form, and whose Premise summarizes the entire story. Your outline can contain other Problem story elements, which are complications, subplots, and sequences. Problem story elements are plotted as a set of Scene story elements that ultimately describe them. At that level, every }{\f2\fs24\b0\i0
scene, with its conflict or value exchange, also presents a problem to be solved. Finding your story problem, and building great scenes, are discussed elsewhere. Developing the middle structure of your story is what the Problem Structure tab is about.}{\f2\fs24
 By putting a beat sheet on each problem story element, StoryCAD helps you to use them to structure your story. We recommend using simplified (\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2 \lquote mini\rquote ) beat sheets for subproblems, where a more complicated beat sheet can work well with the story problem (identified in the Story Overview.)}
\par\plain\f2\fs24
\par\plain{\f2\fs24 To use the Structure Tab, select a beat sheet for your problem using the Structure dropdown. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 We recommend starting at the top, with the story problem which you identified for your Story Overview. }
\par\plain\f2\fs24
\par\plain{\f2\fs24 \{$SCRImageLink[w:680;h:467]=$PROJECT://E8F53F74-2D54-4943-8FC7-A3FDC1C7FC82.png\}}
