\par\plain{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  Repeat this process to fill in as much of the beat sheet as you like.}
\par\plain\f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Here are a few things to keep in mind:}
\par\plain\f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 You can assign either sub-problems or scenes to a beat, and a beat sheet can contain a mixture of the two. Ultimately, you\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2 \rquote re going to have to draft your story from the scenes in your outline, so when you\rquote re assigning a sub-problem, you\rquote re making a promise to yourself to plot that problem into scenes as well. You can use that problem\rquote s Structure tab }{\f2\fs24\b0\i0
to do so. [NOTE: a discussion of the not-yet-written report goes here. The report should integrate the problems\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2 \rquote  beat assignments.]}
\par\plain\f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 A scene can belong to more than one beat. This makes sense since a scene can and should accomplish more than one thing (refer to Purpose of Scene on the Scene form\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2 \rquote s Development tab.). It is also possible to assign a scene to more than one problem, tying them together. However, you can only use a subproblem once, in one (parent) problem. }
\par\plain\f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Not all beats in a beat sheet need to be used. However, when you\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2 \rquote re reviewing your outline, you may find that a plot hole corresponds to a beat you haven\rquote t used. Beat sheets help solve other plotting issues as well, such as lack of structure, pacing issues, weak character arcs, subplot integration, and weak endings. }
